<font color="#FF0000">TO JOHN RATLIFF</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jun 26  6:18:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
The VC were widely supported in the south and represented a large portion of the population. The evidence I present to you is the hundreds of thousands of them who died for their cause. I think that, perhaps, you are the one who is naive when you say that the motivation for them to fight was to have a gun stuck to their heads. The Vietnamese people have been fighting for thousands of years. They full well knew how to fight. We were viewed as the latest of foreign invaders. Look at the corruption (the Diem government) we were supporting. Do you think that those who opposed us had knowledge of American history? Do you think that they had heard of Manifest Destiny? What was running through their minds when the proposed elections of 1956 came and went without being held? Did the bombing in the north weaken the resolve of the people? Or were guns held to their heads?<br><br>
The US had agreed to abide by the Geneva Convention which divided a nation into north and south. This nation was to be reunited with free elections held within 2 years. A nation which hitherto had been one. How can a nation invade itself? It was a civil war.<br><br>
You say that wars are won by the winners. You are correct. The war to oust the French colonials was won by the best organized force in Vietnam at that time - the Viet Minh. The Viet Minh had *won* the war in 1954, had achieved its objective of throwing out the foreigners,  yet got screwed at Geneva and afterwords.<br><br>
As for murders and atrocities, the government of the south was hardly innocent either. Murders and tortures were committed by all factions. <br><br>
If, as you suggest, we would have invaded the north, we  would be fighting there still.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


